1. Cut Size Minimization¶

We would often like to split a network into some partitions to reduce the edges connecting them as much as possible. Since removing the edges between partitions will break the network, the number of the edges between partitions is called the "cut size". The problem of cut size minimization particularly interests electronic engineers because they must divide a large circuit into several smaller and more manageable pieces for industrial manufacture. Here I will demonstrate with two networks.

The first network is the Zachary's karate club [1]. Wayne Zachary, a sociologist, studied the relationships between a karate club's 34 members from 1970 and 1972, so an edge between two members thus captured their relatively closer friendship. During Zachary's study, the club's instructor (yellow) and administrator (cyan) had a conflict, and this led to the club's split. Around half of the members (circles) followed the instructor and started a new karate club, whereas the remaining members (squares) followed the adminstrator or gave up karate.

Decades later, the social network gained much fame because Michelle Girvan and Mark Newman employed it to demonstrate the power of their community detection algorithm [2], which almost correctly predicted the split. You can retrieve this famous network with karate_club_graph(), in which node 0 (Mr. Hi) and node 33 (Officer) respectively represent the instructor and the administrator.

1.1 The Kernighan-Lin algorithm¶

The canonical method to solve the problem is the Kernighan-Lin algorithm [4]. The intuitive idea is to maximize the number of internal edges within the partition, so that the inter-partition edges (cut set) are minimized. The algorithm is as followed:

  1. Given the size of partitions, first divide the network into two arbitrary partitions.

  2. Computes each node's "gain". The gain of node $i$ is defined to be $G_i=E_i-I_i$, if it connects to $E_i$ nodes from other partition and $I_i$ nodes inside its own partition.

  3. By observation, moving a node from one partition to another will make all its internal edges become external edges, while its external edges will become internal edges. Thus swapping two nodes $i$ and $j$ will lead to a gain of number of internal edges of

\begin{align*} g_{ij}=G_i+G_j-2n_{ij} = E_i + E_j - I_i - I_j - 2n_{ij} \end{align*}

where $n_{ij}$ is the number of edges connecting $i$ and $j$, since they always remain as external edges. By computing the gain of all pair of nodes, the algorithm swaps the pair of nodes that gives the highest gain. If no pair increase the gain, the algorithm swaps the pair that decrease the gain the least.

  1. After one swap, the algorithm freezes the swapped nodes so that they will not be swapped again.

  2. The algorithm continues steps 1 to 4 until all nodes are swapped, and the procedure to swap all nodes once is called a pass.

The standard Kernighan-Lin algorithm goes through multiple passes until the cut size increases after a pass. The following block of raw codes demonstrate one pass on Zachary's karate club.

In [4]:
free = list(karate)
part_size = karate.number_of_nodes()//2
bipart = [free[:part_size], free[part_size:]]
A = nx.to_numpy_array(karate)
A2 = A @ A

gain_pass = 0
while len(free) > 0:
    free_bipart = [sorted(list(set(free).intersection(bipart[b]))) for b in [0,1]]
    gain_indv = [np.array([A[n].sum() - 2*A[n, bipart[b]].sum()
                           for n in free_bipart[b]]) for b in [0,1]]
    gain_swap = np.broadcast_to(gain_indv[0].reshape(-1,1), map(len, gain_indv)) \
              + np.broadcast_to(gain_indv[1], map(len, gain_indv)) \
              - 2*A2[np.array(free_bipart[0]).reshape(-1,1), free_bipart[1]]
    
    gain_pass += gain_swap.min()
    coord = gain_swap.argmin()
    u = free_bipart[0][coord // len(gain_indv[0])]
    v = free_bipart[1][coord % len(gain_indv[1])]
    
    del free[free.index(u)], free[free.index(v)]
    bipart[0][bipart[0].index(u)] = v
    bipart[1][bipart[1].index(v)] = u
print('Gain after one pass: %d' % gain_pass)

for i,b in enumerate(bipart):
    for n in b:
        karate.nodes[n]['KL'] = i
b0 = karate.nodes[0]['KL']
        
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.title('One Pass of the KL Algorithm on Zachary\'s Karate Club\n')
nx.draw(karate, pos=karate.graph['pos'], node_size=0, width=.25)
for i,part in enumerate(karate.graph['parts'].values()):
    nx.draw(karate, pos=karate.graph['pos'],
            width=0, edgecolors='k',
            node_size=[k*2000 if n in part else 0
                       for n,k in karate.graph['degs'].items()],
            node_color=[yellow if b==b0 else cyan for n,b in karate.nodes(data='KL')],
            node_shape='s' if i else 'o',
            labels={33:'Ad'} if i else {0:'In'})

Gain after one pass: -44

1.2. Spectral partitioning¶

The problem of cut size minimization can be reformulated in terms of eigenvectors of a network's Laplacian matrix $\mathbf{L}$ [5]. Denote

  • Eigenvalues of $\mathbf{L}$ as $\lambda_1\leq\lambda_2\leq\cdots\leq\lambda_n$
  • The corresponding eigenvectors as $\{\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\cdots \mathbf{v}_n\}$

By the propoerty of $\mathbf{L}$, while $\lambda_1\equiv 0$ and $\mathbf{v}_1\equiv\mathbf{1}$, signs of elements in $\mathbf{v}_2$ naturally divide the network into two partitions that helps reduce the cut size. (In fact, signs of elements in $\mathbf{v}_1\equiv\mathbf{1}$ trivially group all nodes into a single partition, which of course minimizes the cut size.)

In [6]:
for n,b in enumerate(np.linalg.eigh(nx.laplacian_matrix(karate).toarray())[1][:,1]):
    karate.nodes[n]['L'] = b>=0
b0 = karate.nodes[0]['L']

plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.title('Spectral Bipartitioning Zachary\'s Karate Club with Laplacian\n')
nx.draw(karate, pos=karate.graph['pos'], node_size=0, width=.25)
for i,part in enumerate(karate.graph['parts'].values()):
    nx.draw(karate, pos=karate.graph['pos'],
            width=0, edgecolors='k',
            node_size=[k*2000 if n in part else 0
                       for n,k in karate.graph['degs'].items()],
            node_color=[yellow if b==b0 else cyan for n,b in karate.nodes(data='L')],
            node_shape='s' if i else 'o',
            labels={33:'Ad'} if i else {0:'In'})

The magnitude of elements in $\mathbf{v}_2$ actually tell us the "strength" of the corresponding nodes. The larger magnitude $\left(\mathbf{v}_2\right)_i$ has, the more likely $i$ should stay at its partition. Hence, if sizes of the partitions are given, say $n$ versus $\left({N-n}\right)$, one should pack the $n$ nodes represented by the $n$ most positive (or negative) elements in $\mathbf{v}_2$ into the same partition and leave the others in the other partition. The following block of code colours each node according to the magnitudes of their corresponding elements in $\mathbf{v}_2$.

In [7]:
ywc = mpl.colors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('', [yellow, 'w', cyan])
cwy = mpl.colors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('', [cyan, 'w', yellow])

vmin,vmax = 0,0
for n,b in enumerate(np.linalg.eigh(nx.laplacian_matrix(dolphins).toarray())[1][:,1]):
    dolphins.nodes[list(dolphins)[n]]['L'] = b
    if b < vmin: vmin = b
    elif b > vmax: vmax = b

plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.title('Spectral Bipartitioning Dolphins\' Social Network with Laplacian\n')
nx.draw(dolphins, pos=dolphins.graph['pos'], node_size=0, width=.25)
for i,part in dolphins.graph['parts'].items():
    nx.draw(dolphins, pos=dolphins.graph['pos'],
            width=0, edgecolors='k', cmap=ywc,
            node_size=[k*2000 if n in part else 0
                       for n,k in dolphins.graph['degs'].items()],
            node_color= [-b/vmin if b<0 else b/vmax
                         for n,b in dolphins.nodes(data='L')],
            node_shape='^' if i==None else ('s' if i else 'o'))

2. From Partitions to Communities¶

In graph partitioning problems, we are given the number of partitions to cut and sometimes also their sizes. This is fundamentally different from community detection because in this case we rarely know the number of communities and their sizes in advance. The problem of community detection also inevitably raises a philosophical question: what is a "community"?

Here I am demonstrating the with the network striking trade union [6], which consists of 4 young Spanish speakers (yellow sawtooth), 9 young English speakers (white sawtooth), and 11 old English speakers (white round). An edge between two members indicates that they often talked to each other about the strike. The company tried to resolve the strike by negotiating with Sam and Wendle (thick border), but they found this strategy completely ineffective.

2.1 Defining communities at first glance¶

There is no universal definition of "community" upon which everyone agrees. Still, we intuitively think that a community should be a dense subgraph and that a node link to nodes within the same community more frequently than to ones outside. Such intuitions lead to various plausible topological definitions of communities.

In the following sections, $C$ represents some community that contains nodes $\left\{n\right\}$ and has a characteristic number $k$. A node's characteristic number $q$ is subsequently defined as the maximal $k$ of all communities to which it belongs; conversely, communities with $k=q$ are the node's maximal communities. A community is commutative if and only if every node inside has the same $q$.

In [9]:
# the gift-wrapping algorithm; for visualizing communities
def gift_wrap(pts):
    convexHull = []
    ptOnHull = pts[pts[:,0].argmin(), :] # leftmost
    counter_clock = lambda a,b,c: (c[1]-a[1])*(b[0]-a[0]) \
                               >= (b[1]-a[1])*(c[0]-a[0]) # cross product
    while True:
        convexHull.append(ptOnHull)
        endpt = pts[0]
        for j in range(1, len(pts)):
            if np.allclose(endpt, ptOnHull) or \
            not counter_clock(pts[j], convexHull[-1], endpt):
                # pts[j] on the left of (convexHull[-1], endpt)
                endpt = pts[j]
        ptOnHull = endpt
        if np.allclose(endpt, convexHull[0]):
            return np.array(convexHull)

2.1.1. Clique¶

A node's clique-based communities are the cliques to which it belongs.

A $k$-clique is a $k$-node subgraph in which every node links to all the other $\left(k-1\right)$ nodes.

This definition of community is however too restrictive. There are few large cliques in real networks but mostly $2$- and $3$-cliques, i.e. trivial edges and triangles. Furthermore, it is NP-complete to find cliques in a network, meaning that the running time rises exponentially with the network's size.

In [10]:
def clique_community(G, commutative=False):
    Cs = {tuple(C) for Cs in nx.cliques_containing_node(G).values() for C in Cs}
    if commutative:
        Cs = {C for C in Cs if all(nx.node_clique_number(G, n) == len(C) for n in C)}
    return nx.utils.groups(dict((C, len(C)) for C in Cs))

2.1.2. Component¶

A node's component-based communities are the components to which it belongs.

A $k$-component is a subgraph that remains connected before removing $k$ nodes.

In other words, a $k$-component definitely does not break even after removing $\left(k-1\right)$ nodes. The value $k$ is called the component's connectivity.

The $1$-component of a connected graph trivially contains all nodes, and $2$- and $3$-components are commonly referred to as bicomponents and tricomponents. The nodes whose removal breaks a component forms its node cut-set. If a node cut-set only has one node, the only node is called a broker.

In [12]:
def component_community(G, commutative=False):
    Cd = nx.k_components(G) # {k: [{C}]}
    cs = dict((n, max([k for k in Cd for C in Cd[k] if n in C])) for n in G)
    Cs = {tuple(C) for Cs in Cd.values() for C in Cs}
    if commutative:
        Cs = {C for C in Cs if all(cs[n]==nx.node_connectivity(nx.subgraph(G, C)) for n in C)}
    return nx.utils.groups(dict((C, nx.node_connectivity(nx.subgraph(G, C))) for C in Cs))

2.1.3. Edge subgraph¶

A node's edge-subgraph-based communities are the edge subgraphs to which it belongs.

A $k$-edge-subgraph is a subgraph that remains connected before removing $k$ edges.

The value $k$ is called the subgraph's edge connectivity. (On the other hand, a $k$-edge-component cotains nodes with pairwise edge connectivity $k$ on the original graph, meaning that every node in the edge component can reach any other node via at least $k$ edge-disjoint paths on the orignal graph. While a $k$-edge-subgraph is always a $k$-edge-component, the converse generally fails for $k>2$.)

The $1$-edge-subgraph of a connected graph trivially contains all nodes. The edges whose removal breaks an edge subgraph forms its edge cut-set. If an edge cut-set only has one edge, the only edge is called a bridge.

In [14]:
def edge_subgraph_community(G, commutative=True):
    Cd = {}
    for k in range(1, len(G)):
        Cd[k] = [C for C in nx.k_edge_subgraphs(G, k) if len(C)>1] 
        if len(Cd[k]) == 0:
            del Cd[k]
            break
    cs = dict((n, max([k for k in Cd for C in Cd[k] if n in C])) for n in G)
    Cs = {tuple(C) for Cs in Cd.values() for C in Cs}
    if commutative:
        Cs = {C for C in Cs if all(cs[n]==nx.edge_connectivity(nx.subgraph(G, C)) for n in C)}
    return nx.utils.groups(dict((C, nx.edge_connectivity(nx.subgraph(G, C))) for C in Cs))

2.1.4. Core¶

A node's core-based communities are the cores to which it belongs.

A $k$-core is a subgraph in which every node links to $k$ other nodes.

The value $k$ is called the core's coreness.

def core_community(G, commutative=True):
    cs = nx.core_number(G)
    Cs = {tuple(nx.k_core(G, k)) for k in range(min(cs.values()),
                                                max(cs.values())+1)}
    if commutative:
        Cs = {C for C in Cs if all(qs[n]==qs[Q[0]] for n in Q)}
    return dict((min(nx.core_number(nx.subgraph(G, C)).values()), {C}) for C in Cs)

2.2 Assessing communities¶

We have gone through multiple ways to obtain a potential community, i.e. a group of nodes that we think it is a community. Our potential communities look drasticially different based on the concepts we are relying on, e.g. the Kernighan-Lin algorithm, $k$-component. How can we verify if these "potential communities" really represent communities?

2.2.1 Strong and weak communities¶

A node's degree $k$ can be divided into an interior degree $k^\text{int}$, which counts the links between it and nodes from the same community, and an exterior one $k^\text{ext}=k-k^\text{int}$, which counts the links between it and nodes from other communities. A strong community satisfies $k^\text{int} > k^\text{ext}$ for all nodes, whereas a weak community satisfies a weaker condition: $\sum_i {k_i^\text{int}} > \sum_i {k_i^\text{ext}}$. A strong community obviously satisfies the weak community's condition at the same time. We may then define a community's power $p\in\left[0,1\right]$ as

\begin{align*} p = \begin{cases} 1-\min\left({\langle{\dfrac{k^\text{ext}} {k^\text{int}}}\rangle, 1}\right) & \left(\text{strong}\right) \\ 1-\min\left({\dfrac{\sum_n{k_n^\text{ext}}} {\sum_n{k_n^\text{int}}}, 1}\right) & \left(\text{weak}\right) \end{cases}\,, \end{align*}

which tells us how likely it indeed represents a strong or weak community. If a potential community does not satisfy the strong or weak condition, its corresponding power drops to $p=0$. This definition however favours a large community; particularly, a community has $p\equiv1$ if it contains all nodes since $k^\text{ext}=0$. A better quantity hence normalizes the power with the size of the community $n$ and that of the network $N$, i.e.

\begin{align*} \hat{p} = \begin{cases} 1-\min\left({\dfrac{n}{N-n} \langle{\dfrac{k^\text{ext}} {k^\text{int}}}\rangle, 1}\right) & \left(\text{strong}\right) \\ 1-\min\left({\dfrac{n}{N-n} \dfrac{\sum_n{k_n^\text{ext}}} {\sum_n{k_n^\text{int}}}, 1}\right) & \left(\text{weak}\right) \end{cases}\,. \end{align*}

Note that the normalization fails for $n=N$ because it yields $\dfrac{0}{0}$.

In [16]:
def power(G, nbunch, strong=True, normalize=True):
    N, n = len(G), len(nbunch)
    if n == N: return np.nan
    if n == 1: return 0
    f = n/(N-n) if normalize else 1    
    
    kInt = lambda n: nx.subgraph(G, nbunch).degree[n]
    kExt = lambda n: G.degree[n] - kInt(n)
    kInts = np.array([kInt(n) for n in nbunch])
    kExts = np.array([kExt(n) for n in nbunch])
    
    if strong:
        if 0 in kInts: return 0
        return 1 - min(np.mean(kExts/kInts)*f, 1)
    else:
        if kInts.sum() == 0: return 0
        return 1 - min(kExts.sum()/kInts.sum()*f, 1)

2.2.2 Modularity¶

Recall that we have introduced modularity $Q\in\left[-1,1\right]$ as a measure to assortativity.

\begin{align*} Q &= \dfrac{1}{2m} \sum_{i,j} \left( A_{ij} - \dfrac{k_ik_j}{2m} \right) \delta \left(c_i, c_j\right) \end{align*}

To become a measure of community's integrity, we only have to change our wordings from "class $c_i$" to "community $c_i$", i.e.

  • $Q>0$, if actual no. of edges between nodes from the same community > average
  • $Q<0$, if actual no. of edges between nodes from the same community < average

The definition can be alternatively reformulated as

\begin{align*} Q = \sum_c {\left[\dfrac{m_c}{m} -\left(\dfrac{K_c}{2m}\right)^2\right]}\,, \end{align*}

where each potential community $c$ contains $m_c$ edges and some nodes with a total degree $K_c$ on the original network [7]. The summand inside bracket is also referred to as a single community $c$'s modularity $Q_c$. From this reformulation, we see two special cases:

  1. If all nodes are grouped as a single community, $K_c=2m$ and $m_c=m$, leads to $Q=0$.
  2. If every node is classified as a separate community, $m_c\equiv0$ leads to $Q<0$.
In [17]:
def modularity(G, communities, matrix=False):
    E = G.number_of_edges()
    Qs = communities
    if matrix:
        B = nx.modularity_matrix(G)
        D = np.array([[1 if i in Q else 0 for Q in Qs] for i in G])
        return np.trace(D.T@B@D)/(2*E)
    else:
        M = 0
        for Q in Qs:
            H = nx.subgraph(G, Q)
            EQ = H.number_of_edges()
            KQ = sum(G.degree[n] for n in H)
            M += EQ/E-(KQ/(2*E))**2
        return M
    
def modularity_single(G, community):
    E = G.number_of_edges()
    H = nx.subgraph(G, community)
    EQ = H.number_of_edges()
    KQ = sum(G.degree[n] for n in H)
    return EQ/E-(KQ/(2*E))**2


# return the modularity of the 4 closely joined members
print(modularity_single(strike, ['Alejandro', 'Carlos', 'Domingo', 'Eduardo']))

0.12863573407202214

Modularity helps measure how well an $n$-partition represents $n$ communities. In fact, this effectiveness of modularity relies on the fundamental hypothesis for community detection:

A random network lacks communities.

Recalling that modularity is a measure to the difference between the expected number of edges on a random graph and the actual number. Therefore modularity sets random network as the reference point of edge density and thus identifies community: if the subgraph is denser than its random counterpart, it is more likely for the subgraph to represent a real community than not to represent any.

3. Modularity Maximization¶

Although there is no agreement upon the definition of a community, network scientists commonly agree that modularity well assesses a potential community. Given its importance, various algorithms are devoted to maximize it.

3.1 Spectral partitioning¶

We can maximize a bipartition's modularity by inspecting the eigenvector $\mathbf{v}_N$ associated with the largest eigenvalue $\beta_N$ of a network's modularity matrix $\mathbf{B} = \mathbf{A}-\dfrac{1}{2E}kk^\intercal$ [5]. If $\mathrm{sign}{\left[\left(\mathbf{v}_N\right)_i\right]}=\mathrm{sign}{\left[\left(\mathbf{v}_N\right)_j\right]}$, nodes $i$ and $j$ belong to the same partition. The magnitude $\lvert{\left({\mathbf{v}_N}\right)_i}\rvert$, as same as the case for a Laplacian matrix's spectrum, indicates how strongly node $i$ is affiliated to its partition.

In fact, after some matrix analysis, the spectral method can be generalized to maximize the modularity of a $n$-partition with an arbitrary $n$. Read Newman's derivation if you are interested [5].

In [18]:
vmin,vmax = 0,0
for n,b in enumerate(np.linalg.eigh(np.asarray(nx.modularity_matrix(karate)))[1][:,-1]):
    karate.nodes[list(karate)[n]]['B'] = b
    if b < vmin: vmin = b
    elif b > vmax: vmax = b

3.2 The Newman algorithm¶

Starting with every node as an individual community, the Newman algorithm iteratively joins the pair of connected communities that can increase modularity $Q$ the most [8]. The $n$-parition with the highest $Q$ is deemed the optimal parition. The following block of code impelements the algorithm. (My implementation is inefficient, though.)

In [19]:
def newman(G):
    hierarchy = [[[n] for n in G]] # [Qs] = [[Q]] = [[[nodes]]]
    Ms = [modularity(G, hierarchy[-1])]
    idx_by_node = dict((n, i) for i,n in enumerate(G))
    Q_by_idx = dict((idx, list(Q)) for idx, Q in nx.utils.groups(idx_by_node).items())
    
    for i in range(G.number_of_nodes()-2):
        Ms.append(-1)
        checked_pairs = []   
        for u, v in G.edges:
            a, b = idx_by_node[u], idx_by_node[v]
            if a != b and {a, b} not in checked_pairs:
                checked_pairs.append({a, b})
                Qs_trial = [Q_by_idx[a] + Q_by_idx[b]] \
                         + [Q_by_idx[c] for c in Q_by_idx if c not in [a, b]]
                M = modularity(G, Qs_trial)
                if M > Ms[-1]:
                    Ms[-1] = M
                    a_propose, b_propose = a, b
                    Qs_propose = Qs_trial                  
        hierarchy.append(Qs_propose)
        min_, max_ = min(a_propose, b_propose), max(a_propose, b_propose)
        Q_by_idx[min_] = [n for n in Q_by_idx[min_]] \
                       + [n for n in Q_by_idx[max_]]
        # I tried 'extend' but it led to some bugs that I could not solve
        # so I resorted to this clumsy way of assignment
        for n in Q_by_idx[max_]:
            idx_by_node[n] = min_
        del Q_by_idx[max_]       
    return hierarchy[Ms.index(max(Ms))]

The Newman algorithm is in fact computationally expensive: it costs a running time of $\mathcal{O}{\left[\left({E+N}\right)N\right]}$ ($E$ = no. of edges, $N$ = no. of nodes). Newman later improved his algorithm with Clauset and Moore and invented the Clauset-Newman-Moore Algorithm [9], which runs in a time of $\mathcal{O}{\left(N(\log{N})^2\right)}$. You can call it with community.greedy_modularity_communities.

3.3 The Louvain algorithm¶

Blonde et al., who are all from the University of Louvain, Belgium, proposed the Louvain Algorithm, which maximizes modularity in a running time of $\mathcal{O}{\left(N\log{N}\right)}$ [10]. With every node initialized as an individual community, the Louvain algorithm iteratively carries out the following steps:

  1. Move node $i$ to the community of one of its neighbours $j$ such that the corresponding change in modularity $\Delta_{ij}$ is positive and maximized. If $\Delta_{ij}<0$ for all $j$, do not move $i$.
  2. Repeat step 1 for all $i$ sequentially until $\Delta_{ij}<0$ for all pairs of $\left(i,j\right)$.
  3. Transform the original network to a weighted network, in which each node represents a proposed community. The inter-community edges become weighted edges between nodes, whereas the intra-community edges become weighted self-loops; the weights equal to the number of edges.

The three steps form one pass, and the algorithm terminates once the network remains unchanged after step 3. The nodes of the final weighted network represents the potential communities.

Suppose nodes $i$ and $j$ belong to communities $I$ and $J$ before a move. The change in modularity $\Delta_{ij}$ is the sum of the change $\Delta_I^{-i}$ due to removing $i$ from $I$ and the change $\Delta_J^{+i}$ due to adding $i$ to $J$, i.e. $\Delta_{ij}=\Delta_I^{-i}+\Delta_J^{+i}$. On a weighted network with a total weight $W$,

\begin{align*} \Delta_J^{+i} = \dfrac{k_i^J}{W} - {\left({\dfrac {w_J+k_i}{2W}}\right)}^2 + \left({\dfrac{w_J}{2W}}\right)^2 + \left({\dfrac{k_i}{2W}}\right)^2 \,, \end{align*}

where $k_i$ is the total weight of $i$'s edges, i.e. its weighted degree, and $k_i^J$ the total weight of $i$'s edges linking to nodes in $J$. Then $w_J$ sums up the weighted degrees of nodes in $J$, i.e. $w_J=\sum_{j\in J}{k_j}$. Finally, $\Delta_I^{-i}=-\Delta_{I^\prime}^{+i}$ if $I$ becomes $I^\prime$ after removing $i$.

In [24]:
def louvain(G):
    H = G.copy()
    for c,i in enumerate(H):
        H.nodes[i]['louvain'] = c
    for u,v,w in H.edges(data='weight'):
        H[u][v]['weight'] = 1 if w==None else w
    
    K_func = lambda i: sum(H[i][j]['weight'] for j in H[i] if j!=i)\
                     + (2*H[i][i]['weight'] if i in H[i] else 0)
    K = dict((i, K_func(i)) for i in H)
    k = lambda i,J: sum(H[i][j]['weight'] for j in H[i] if j in J)
    w = lambda J: sum(K[j] for j in J)
    
    def delta_J_add_i(i, J):
        ki, wJ = K[i], w(J)
        return k(i,J)/W + (wJ**2+ki**2-(wJ+K[i])**2)/(2*W)**2
    def delta_I_minus_i(i):
        return -delta_J_add_i(i, [j for j in Qs[H.nodes[i]['louvain']] if j!=i])
    def try_to_move(i):
        dImi = delta_I_minus_i(i)
        delta = dict((j, dImi+delta_J_add_i(i,Qs[H.nodes[j]['louvain']])) for j in H[i] if j!=i)
        deltaMax = max(delta.values())
        if deltaMax > 0:
            j = list(delta.keys())[list(delta.values()).index(deltaMax)]
            if H.nodes[i]['louvain'] == H.nodes[j]['louvain']:
                return False
            Qs[H.nodes[i]['louvain']].remove(i)
            Qs[H.nodes[j]['louvain']].add(i)
            H.nodes[i]['louvain'] = H.nodes[j]['louvain']
        else:
            return False
    
    W = sum(w for u,v,w in H.edges(data='weight'))
    Qs = nx.utils.groups(nx.get_node_attributes(H, 'louvain'))
    move = True
    while move:
        for i in H:
            move = try_to_move(i)
    
    T = nx.Graph(dict((Q, {}) for Q in Qs if len(Qs[Q])>0))
    for idxI,I in enumerate(T):
        T.add_edge(I, I, weight=sum(H[i][j]['weight'] for i in Qs[I]
                                    for j in H[i] if j in Qs[I]))
        for idxJ in range(idxI):
            J = list(T)[idxJ]
            T.add_edge(I, J, weight=sum(H[i][j]['weight'] for i in Qs[I]
                                        for j in H[i] if j in Qs[J]))
            
    if nx.is_isomorphic(H, T):
        T.graph['louvain'] = Qs
        return T
    else:
        Qs = louvain(T).graph['louvain']
        for i,L in H.nodes(data='louvain'):
            for Q in Qs:
                if L in Qs[Q]:
                    H.nodes[i]['louvain'] = Q
                    break
        H.graph['louvain'] = nx.utils.groups(nx.get_node_attributes(H, 'louvain'))
        return H

3.4 Resolution limit of modularity¶

Before ending, we must discuss the major drawback of using modularity: it almost prohibits the existence of small communities due to its resolution limit, while there are no physical reasons to ban them. In fact, if we merge two communities $A$ and $B$ that have total degrees $K_A$ and $K_B$, the resulting change in modularity reads

\begin{align*} \Delta_{AB} &= \dfrac{E_{AB}}{m} - \dfrac{K_AK_B}{2m^2} \\ &\sim m_{AB} - \dfrac{K_AK_B}{2m} \,, \end{align*}

where the two communities are connected with $m_{AB}$ edges. Once $K_AK_B<2m$, the change $\Delta_{AB}$ is positive as long as at least one edge connects $A$ and $B$, i.e. $m_{AB}=1$. This physically means that a network's modularity can be increased by merging two barely connected small communities. Consequently, a communitity with a total degree $K<\sqrt{2m}$ cannot be observed through modularity maximization. In other words, a network probably has fewer large communities but more small communities than what modularity maximization suggests.

4. Hierarchical Clustering¶

By iteratively bipartitioning it, we can translate a network into a hierarchy of "intimacy", in which two nodes are closer to each other if they are more likely belong to the same partition. This approach is generally called "hierarchical clustering". To demonstrate this idea, I will use a small toy network shown below. Intuitively, nodes {0, 1, 2} should belong to the same partition, so should {3, 4, 5} and {6, 7, 8, 9}, but the case becomes ambiguous for node 10.

In [27]:
toy = nx.disjoint_union_all([nx.cycle_graph(3), nx.cycle_graph(3),
                             nx.cycle_graph(4)])
toy.add_edges_from([(10,v) for v in [2,3,7]] + [(5,6), (7,9)])

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
plt.title('A Toy Network\n')
nx.draw_kamada_kawai(toy, node_color='w', edgecolors='k', with_labels=True)

There are two ways to build a hierarchy an agglomerative (bottom-up) approach and a divisive (top-down) approach. The former iteratively group nodes and partitions into larger partitions until all nodes belong to the same partition, whereas the latter iteratively divides the network and subsequent partitions into two until all nodes become an isolated partition.

While the Kernighan-Lin algorithm divides a graph according to cut size, the algorithms that I am going to cover employ other criteria.

4.1 The Ravasz algorithm¶

The Ravasz algorithm employs the agglomerative approach and builds a hierarchy according to similarity between partitions [11]. In short, starting from every node as an isolated partition, the Ravasz algorithm continuously groups the two most "similar" partitions into a larger one until all nodes become one single partition.

What does "similarity between partitions", though? This notion is defined upon "nodal similarity", which we have slightly gone through in Tutorial 2; we learnt to measure two nodes' similarity with Salton's cosine, Pearson correlation coefficient, and Euclidean distance then. If partitions $P$ and $Q$ repsectively have nodes $\left\{p_i\right\}$ and $\left\{q_j\right\}$, the similarity between the partitions $s{\left(P,Q\right)}$ may be defined in three ways:

  1. simple clustering, i.e. $s{\left(P,Q\right)}=\min_{i,j} s{\left(p_i,q_j\right)}$,
  2. complete clustering, i.e. $s{\left(P,Q\right)}=\max_{i,j} s{\left(p_i,q_j\right)}$, and
  3. average clustering, i.e. $s{\left(P,Q\right)}=\langle{s{\left(p_i,q_j\right)}}\rangle$.

Here $s$ refers to the similarity measure that you are using. Ravasz et al.'s paper employs the so-called overlap coefficient $\omega$: for an adjacency matrix $\mathbf{A}$ and a degree vector $\mathbf{k}$,

\begin{align*} \omega_{ij}=\dfrac{n_{ij}+A_{ij}} {\min{\left(k_i,k_j\right)}+1-A_{ij}}\,, \end{align*}

where $i$ and $j$ share $n_{ij}$ neighbours. If the adjacency of $i$ contains or is contained by that of $j$, $\omega{\left(i,j\right)}=1$; if the two nodes are not connected and share no common neighbours, $\omega_{ij}=0$. (I prefer calling this metric "subset coefficient" instead.)

In [28]:
def overlap_coefficient(G, u, v):
    a = int(G.has_edge(u, v))
    j = len(list(nx.common_neighbors(G, u, v))) + a
    ku, kv = G.degree(u), G.degree(v)
    return j/(min(ku,kv)+1-a)

def similarity(G, c1, c2, method=None, clustering=None):
    method = overlap_coefficient if method == None else method
    S = [[method(G, n1, n2) for n2 in c2] for n1 in c1]
    if clustering == 'single':
        return np.min(S)
    elif clustering == 'complete':
        return np.max(S)
    else:
        return np.mean(S)

def ravasz(G, method=None, clustering=None):
    N = G.number_of_nodes()
    tree = [{n} for n in G]
    while len(tree) > 1:
        yield tuple(tree)
        L = len(tree)
        S = -np.ones((L,L), float)
        for i in range(L):
            for j in range(i):
                S[i,j] = similarity(G, tree[i], tree[j], method, clustering)
        coord = S.argmax()
        i,j = coord%L,coord//L
        tree[i] = tree[i].union(tree[j])
        del tree[j]

toy.graph['ravasz'] = list(ravasz(toy))
print('The Ravasz algorithm on the toy network (average overlap coefficient):')

The Ravasz algorithm assigns node 10 in the toy network into the group of nodes {0, 1, 2}. However, as you may see, the performance of the algorithm highly depends on the input order of the nodes. For example, suppose nodes $s$, $t$, $u$, and $v$ are pairwise similar; at the level of bipartition, the algorithm probably returns $\left(\left\{s,t\right\},\left\{u,v\right\}\right)$ if I input $\left\{s,t,u,v\right\}$ but $\left(\left\{s,u\right\},\left\{t,v\right\}\right)$ if I input $\left\{s,u,t,v\right\}$.

A hierarchy can be clearly illustrated with a dendrogram, which is unfortunately hard to draw with Python. Here I demonstrate how to draw one with scipy.cluster.hierarchy.dendrogram(). For an $N$-node network, the method takes in an $(N-1)\times4$ "linkage matrix" $\mathbf{Z}$. Each row of $Z$ represents a join of two labeled partitions: on the $i$th row, the first two entries $Z_{i1}$ and $Z_{i2}$ are the indexes of two the two nodes/partition that are joining. The partition formed by them is then indexed as $(i+N-1)$ (-1 since partition index starting at 0). The next two entries, $Z_{i3}$ marks its height in the dendrogram, while $Z_{i4}$ records the number of nodes inside this newly formed partition.

The following block of code shows the iteration of the above network. The output of $Z$ can be read as

  • 1st row: node 0 (indexed as partition 0) and node 1 (indexed as partition 1) join up to become the partition 11
  • 2nd row: partition 11 and node 2 (indexed as partition 2) join to become partition 12
  • 8th row: partition 12 and node 10 (indexed as partition 10) join to become partiton 18

And so you can see the nodes 0,1,2,10 join as a large partition, displaying in the dendrogram. The height is set to be $r-1$, where $r$ is the order after ranking of the partition's size.

Please read the method's documenation for more information.

In [30]:
from scipy.cluster import hierarchy

def to_linkage(tuples_of_sets, height='rank'):
    N = len(tuples_of_sets[0])
    Z = np.zeros((N-1,4), float)
    record = list(tuples_of_sets[0])
    
    for i in range(N-2):
        idxs,sets = [],[]
        for set_ in tuples_of_sets[i]:
            if set_ not in tuples_of_sets[i+1]:
                idxs.append(record.index(set_))
                sets.append(set_)
        record += [sets[0].union(sets[1])]
        Z[i,:2] = idxs
        Z[i,-1] = len(record[-1])
    Z[-1,:2] = [record.index(set_) for set_ in tuples_of_sets[-1]]
    Z[-1,-1] = N
    
    if height == 'rank':
        track = sorted(list(set(Z[:,3])))
        Z[:,2] = [track.index(Z[i,3])+1 for i in range(N-1)]
    else: # height == 'size'
        Z[:,2] = Z[:,3]-1
    return Z


# print the linkage matrix
print(to_linkage(toy.graph['ravasz']))

                     color_threshold=0, above_threshold_color='k')

# the Laplacian matrix is used instead of the adjacency matrix here
def overlap_distance(Li, Lj):
    i,j = np.argmax(Li>0), np.argmax(Lj>0)
    Ai,Aj = -Li,-Lj
    Ai[i],Aj[j] = 0,0
    c = np.sum(Ai*Aj)
    return 1-(c+Ai[j])/(min(Li[i],Lj[j])+1-Ai[j])

Z = hierarchy.linkage(nx.laplacian_matrix(toy).toarray(),
                      method='average', metric=overlap_distance)
track = sorted(list(set(Z[:,3])))
Z[:,2] = [track.index(Z[i,3])+1 for i in range(Z.shape[0])]

plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))

Furthermore, you can generalize the Ravasz algorithm by setting parameters method and metric. Please check its documentation to see what values they can take. The following block of code grows the hierarchy according to the Jaccard coefficient $J$ between nodes and partitions:

\begin{align*} J_{ij} = \dfrac{\lvert\mathbf{A}_i\cap\mathbf{A}_j\rvert} {\lvert\mathbf{A}_i\cup\mathbf{A}_j\rvert} = \dfrac{n_{ij}}{k_i+k_j-n_{ij}}\,, \end{align*}

where $\mathbf{A}_i$ denotes $i$'s adjacency. The coefficient approaches $1$ if $i$ and $j$ share more common neighbours, otherwise it shrinks to $0$. The height of each join in the dendrogram below indicates the Jaccard distance $D_J=1-J$ between the two nodes or partitions that it connects.

4.2 The Girvan-Newman algorithm¶

In contrast to the Ravasz algorithm, the Girvan-Newman algorithm employs the divisive approach and keeps dividing a network by successively deleting the most important edge [2]. Which edge is the most important in the network, though? Girvan and Newman considers the betweenness of nodes and generalizes it for edges: an important edge is traversed by many paths and thus have a high edge betweenness. Formally, the edge betweenness $b{\left(e\right)}$ of an edge $e$ reads, up to some normalization constant,

\begin{align*} b{\left(e\right)} \sim \sum_{s<t}{\dfrac{g_{st}{\left(e\right)}} {g_{st}}}\,, \end{align*}

where $g_{st}$ counts the number of shortest paths between nodes $s$ and $t$, and $g_{st}{\left(e\right)}$ similarly counts the ones that traverse $e$. Just like how the ordinary node betweenness may be extended to random walk betweenness, the mentioned edge betweenness may also be extended random walk edge betweenness $r{\left(e\right)}$: for $e=\left(u,v\right)$,

\begin{align*} r{\left(e\right)} \sim \sum_{s<t} \lvert{\Gamma_{us}-\Gamma_{ut}-\Gamma_{vs}+\Gamma_{vt}}\rvert\,, \end{align*}

where $\mathbf{\Gamma}=\left(\mathbf{D}-\mathbf{A}+\mathbf{1}\right)^{-1}$. The edge betweenness of edges is recalculated after deleting each edge.

You may call the Girvan-Newman algorithm with community.girvan_newman(). The method by default uses the ordinary edge betweenness, but you may require it to use the random walk edge betweenness by setting most_valueable_edge accordingly.

In [34]:
#toy.graph['GN'] = list(nx.community.girvan_newman(toy))[::-1]

#''' # alternatively
def random_walk_edge_betweenness(G):
    betweenness = {}
    for c in nx.connected_components(G):
        component = nx.subgraph(G,c)
        betweenness = {**betweenness,
                       **nx.edge_current_flow_betweenness_centrality(component,
                                                                     normalized=False)}
    return max(betweenness, key=betweenness.get)
toy.graph['GN'] = list(nx.community.girvan_newman(toy, most_valuable_edge=
                                                       random_walk_edge_betweenness))[::-1]
#'''
